snippet.textDisplay: The food color would have worked if she hadn’t diluted it so much. The gel color is made to color with a tiny bit of pigment. So it made the conditioner look pink very quickly. But she needed WAY more of the food color to do anything. Think of how dark pink hair dye looks to wash out to a lighter pink. She made the conditioner the final color she wanted and she needed to make it about 20 shades deeper.

I just have to publicly confess that my friend and I, at age 12 (in the 90s) dyed our hair with RIT fabric dye. She was a natural level 12 blonde (albino), me a level 4 brunette. We both ended up with blue and red stripes that were unmistakable, though very different, and VERY permanent in our hair.
But also. Our hands. And clothes. And her bathroom.

Do not recommend.

snippet.textDisplay: My mom and grandma used to bleach their hair with hydrogen peroxide and dye it with organic henna and make beer and olive oil conditioners and it worked out surprisingly well for them? My mom does box dye now but my grandma's hair is hella smooth and thick, especially considering her age and the amount of hairspray she uses. I only did the peroxide thing (I'm dark-medium blonde) and it worked out really great after I used a toning shampoo and deep conditioner (I inspected my ends and it seems like my hair is less damaged than when I did a box lightener which was surprising). Its defiantly not for everyone but its one hell of an adventure and can pay off if you happen to be broke or just in the mood to fight your hair in more creative ways than manic panic or bangs.

snippet.textDisplay:
My hair is currently food coloring dyed and it's kinda perfect...
I used to pay a lot on the salon and the color would wash off after like 2 weeks so it's a waste of money...
The girl in the video did it completely wrong... If I had to guess maybe it's because the conditioner doesn't let the color stay in her hair...
That's why you should use Aloe Vera instead and let me tell you... It might not be as vibrant but the red food coloring gave me a gorgeous rose gold looking color but a bit more pink

snippet.textDisplay: My grandma said that back in the day in the ye olde USSR when they didnt have any hair products they used to boil herbs (specifically chamomile to lighten and nettle to darken) and wash their hair in that. The “shampoo” proccess was once in a while they’d scrub their hair with laundry soap(aka the only soap they had) and then wash it through with herb water to “condition” it. If anyone wants to try this i bet it would be a cool video!

snippet.textDisplay: I dyed my hair with beet juice and henna and I ended up with burgundy. It is a lot darker than the red-orange I have been doing with henna for at least 5 years and now I wish I had recorded the process so you could watch and see a successful dye with beet juice. I think it was successful because it was mixed with 100% pure henna which absorbs (and holds onto hair) really well.

snippet.textDisplay:
The only household thing that works is hot koolaid. Bruh, you’ll cut it out before it fades out.

How to: mix a packet into water, but not the entire amount called for, the less water, the brighter the color, make sure it’s hot (like boiled/steaming hot), dip in lightened hair for 10 min, it’ll be there for 6 months and smell fruity for 2 weeks.
